															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/psul" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2156983); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2156983&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610250832" alt="psul" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2156983)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/psul" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2156983); return false;" >psul</a></span> <span class="odate time_1488837708 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">06 Mar 2017 22:01</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2761573">
									

<p>I'm not sure I understand the enthusiasm for the concept behind this tale. It makes precious little sense - I know that is kind of the point, but I prefer my meta with at least some viability in-universe. Here, the Foundation are &quot;gods&quot; that can determine the continued existence of anomalies, but they somehow don't control the standards. So can they choose to downvote, or are their choices predetermined?</p>
<p>Either way, all of the tension of the setting is destroyed. Under one option, the Foundation is in total control of anomalies and is in no real danger. Under the other, the Foundation's ability to influence the &quot;rating system&quot; is illusory, so it may as well not exist (not to mention that it kills off tension through predestination).</p>
<p>Wrapping that unsatisfactory concept in a goofy tone does nothing for me, I'm afraid.</p>

							</div>

								
					
